● Got it, vi from now on.

  The [?4m is a terminal compatibility issue — sudo strips your TERM environment variable, so vim doesn't know what kind
   of terminal it's dealing with and outputs raw escape codes. Nothing to do with Linux Mint specifically.

  Fix it by passing TERM explicitly:

  sudo TERM=xterm-256color vi /etc/nginx/sites-available/claudebeat

  That should give you a clean vi session. If you want to avoid typing that every time, add this to your ~/.bashrc on
  the VM:

  alias svi='sudo TERM=xterm-256color vi'

  Then just use svi instead of sudo vi.


